
 Identifying the maximum edge biclique in bipartite graphs, a complete bipartite subgraph with the largest number of edges, plays a crucial role in uncovering densely-connected communities and has significant applications in domains such as recommendation systems and biological network analysis. However, this problem is NP-hard, and existing methods face inefficiencies both in practice and theory. In this paper, we propose two novel algorithms with distinct branching strategies and provable time guarantees for solving the maximum edge biclique search problem. The first is a refined pivot-based branching algorithm that systematically exploits vertex adjacency relationships to bound the search for the maximum edge biclique, achieving a time complexity of
